comments.body:
We need `idsToCancel` for the case when a user cancels an optimization before any optimization ids have been generated, but a refresh interval is in the queue waiting to fire a few seconds later.

If we exclude the `idsToCancel.includes(routeIdInOptimizationMode)`, the only way we clear a refresh interval is by checking if the pending optimization is `cancelled`:
 
```
if (refreshOptimization?.status === 'cancelled') {
   clearInterval(interval);
   resolve();
   return;
}
```

But if a user doesn't have any optimization ids collected, we skip the call to the backend to cancel those optimizations (because they don't exist), and then remove the`routeIdInOptimizationMode` from the collection of ids being optimized:

```
const cancelOptimization = async (routeId: number, lateralId?: number) => {
    const routeIdInOptimization = lateralId || routeId;

    const optimizationIds = routesInOptimizationMode.find(
      (route) => route.routeId === routeIdInOptimization,
    )?.optimizationIds;

    if (optimizationIds) {
      await Promise.all(
        optimizationIds.map(async (optimizationId) => {
          await cancelSegmentOptimization(projectId, routeId, optimizationId, lateralId);
          return Promise.resolve();
        }),
      );
    }
    
    removeOptimizedRoute(routeIdInOptimization);
  };
```

However, this means that the given route's pending optimization was never changed to "cancelled" on the backend. Therefore, when a pending refresh interval on the queue fires, it will never clear its interval. `idsToCancel` is a way for us to keep a memory of the ids that were canceled so that way any queued refresh intervals reads from there instead of the pending optimization status.

